                            <comment id="17631207" author="elyograg" created="Wed, 9 Nov 2022 18:25:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Patch that doesn&apos;t include mods to CHANGES.txt.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631211" author="epugh" created="Wed, 9 Nov 2022 18:31:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;nice to see this fix..&#160;&#160; i used to be an eclipse user, and recently tried it again with solr and bumped into the issue...&#160;&#160; Not everyone can afford/has access to IntelliJ.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631221" author="elyograg" created="Wed, 9 Nov 2022 18:50:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I do have an IntelliJ license, as they are nice enough to give it to Apache committers.  But the problem I run into trying to use it is that I have no idea how to do the things that I can do in eclipse easily because I learned how a long time ago.  I could probably learn do the same with IntelliJ, but it&apos;s just easier to use what I know.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631230" author="ichattopadhyaya" created="Wed, 9 Nov 2022 19:00:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for tackling this. I had to migrate from Eclipse to IntelliJ only because of main/branch_9x.&lt;br/&gt;
I would love to be back to Eclipse. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is it possible to run JUnit tests from within Eclipse after this patch? It was my biggest complain, why I had to move away.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631267" author="elyograg" created="Wed, 9 Nov 2022 20:23:24 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Is it possible to run JUnit tests from within Eclipse after this patch? It was my biggest complain, why I had to move away.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Looks like in the latest eclipse (not sure about earlier versions) you can right click on a test class or an individual test method, go to RunAs, and choose JUnit.&#160; And it can be done from the &quot;Run&quot; menu as well.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631298" author="elyograg" created="Wed, 9 Nov 2022 21:23:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In the org.apache.solr.util.configuration package in the hadoop-auth module, I renamed SSLConfigurationsTest.java to HadoopAuthSSLConfigurationsTest.java because eclipse complained about a duplicate class name.&#160; Is that an acceptable class name?&#160; Would it be better to change the package instead?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have this for CHANGES.txt ... is it too verbose?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-none&quot;&gt;
* SOLR-16540: Fix errors when importing into eclipse.  One test class had the same name as another test class
  and there were three instances where a package-info.java file was included on a package in the test tree
  and the same package in the main source tree already had a package-info.java file.&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631326" author="alex.parvulescu" created="Wed, 9 Nov 2022 22:50:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;While on the topic of Eclipse. were you able to convince gradle to download sources for the project? I was able to generate eclipse project and import it but I am missing the sources and it drives me nuts sometimes.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631401" author="elyograg" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 02:37:51 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;were you able to convince gradle to download sources&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve tried a few different things to get it to do that, but nothing has so far worked.&#160; I would like to find a way that doesn&apos;t require adding tons of lines to lots of build.gradle files.&#160; It would be nice if eclipse could load the source code for Solr&apos;s dependencies.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631406" author="alex.parvulescu" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 02:50:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I agree, without sources for dependencies it&apos;s a very subpar experience. I am assuming this script needs an update &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;0&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; but I can&apos;t make much sense of it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;0&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/solr/blob/main/gradle/ide/eclipse.gradle#L33&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/solr/blob/main/gradle/ide/eclipse.gradle#L33&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631408" author="elyograg" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 02:55:25 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Based on what I found with Google, I did this modification as it looked the most promising:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-none&quot;&gt;
diff --git a/gradle/ide/eclipse.gradle b/gradle/ide/eclipse.gradle
index 3721c3184aa..1c1b626048b 100644
--- a/gradle/ide/eclipse.gradle
+++ b/gradle/ide/eclipse.gradle
@@ -31,6 +31,8 @@ configure(rootProject) {
     }
 
     classpath {
+      downloadSources = true
+      downloadJavadoc = true
       defaultOutputDir = file(&apos;build/eclipse&apos;)
 
       file {
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Then I deleted the project from eclipse, ran &quot;./gradlew clean cleanEclipse eclipse&quot; again, and re-imported into eclipse. It didn&apos;t work.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631413" author="elyograg" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 03:02:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;If we do manage to figure out how to get gradle to download source/javadoc jars so IDE context goodies work well, it will be important that those jars do not end up in the finished binary tarball.&#160; The Solr download is already pretty big due to dependencies, and those would make it even larger.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631414" author="alex.parvulescu" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 03:03:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;yep. I also tried the exact same approach with no luck.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631420" author="elyograg" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 03:25:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I did decide that the detail in CHANGES.txt was too verbose.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631425" author="elyograg" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 03:32:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Running ./gradlew check. Hope it passes!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The only concern I have is around the test class rename.&#160; I think that changing the package would also fix it, but that might produce a much larger patch, and I&apos;m not sure which package to change and what to change it to.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631432" author="elyograg" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 03:47:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;New patch.&#160; There were new commits to pull down.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Changing package names in the hadoop-auth test tree was not as intrusive a change as I had feared and looks like an overall beneficial change.&#160; Now it&apos;s more like what&apos;s in the module&apos;s java tree, and eliminates the duplicate class error.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also added the issue to CHANGES.txt.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17631807" author="risdenk" created="Thu, 10 Nov 2022 17:37:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=elyograg&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;elyograg&quot;&gt;elyograg&lt;/a&gt; I don&apos;t think these two changes are correct:&lt;/p&gt;


